import java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit;
import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock;

class MyThread extends Thread {
    static ReentrantLock l = new ReentrantLock();
    String name;

    MyThread(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public void run() {
        // The "do-while" loop ensures we keep trying until we succeed
        do {
            try {
                // Try to acquire the lock for 5000 milliseconds (5 seconds)
                if (l.tryLock(5000, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS)) {
                    System.out.println(name + " ... got the lock");
                    
                    try {
                        // Critical Section: Simulate work (like a Salesforce API call)
                        Thread.sleep(30000); // 30 seconds
                    } finally {
                        // Always unlock!
                        System.out.println(name + " ... releasing the lock");
                        l.unlock();
                        break; // Exit the loop because we finished the work
                    }
                } else {
                    // This runs if the lock was held by someone else for the full 5 seconds
                    System.out.println(name + " ... unable to get lock, will try again");
                }
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                // If the thread is interrupted while waiting for the lock
                Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
                break;
            }
        } while (true);
    }
}

Key Improvements Made:
 * Try-Finally Block: I moved l.unlock() into a finally block. In your notes, if Thread.sleep() threw an error, the lock would stay stuck forever. The finally block ensures the "key" is always returned.
 * TimeUnit: Used TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS for better readability.
 * Corrected Variable Name: Your notes used l.reluxdone, which I've updated to a standard print statement for clarity.
 * Static Lock: I made the lock static. As we discussed, this ensures all threads are fighting for the same lock, rather than each having their own.
How this behaves in the real world:
Imagine Thread A starts and grabs the lock for 30 seconds.
 * Thread B arrives and waits for 5 seconds (the tryLock timeout).
 * After 5 seconds, Thread B fails to get the lock.
 * Because of your do-while loop, Thread B immediately prints "unable to get lock" and tries again for another 5 seconds.
 * This repeats until Thread A is finally done.
